            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this UK National Insurance calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates how much National Insurance (NI) you
                pay based on your gross earnings and employment status. It
                supports:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Employees (Class 1)</strong> – NI deducted through
                  PAYE, plus employer contributions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Self‑employed</strong> – simplified Class 2 and Class
                  4 contributions based on annual profits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Company directors</strong> – treated here as employees
                  with annualised earnings (simplified model).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Employee National Insurance (Class 1)</h3>
              <p>
                For employees, Class 1 NI is charged on your earnings between
                the <em>primary threshold</em> and the
                <em>upper earnings limit</em>, with a lower rate above that
                limit.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Step 1 – Convert pay to annual equivalent</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  If you are paid monthly or weekly, the calculator converts
                  your pay to an annual figure:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Annual pay (monthly) = monthly pay × 12</li>
                  <li>Annual pay (weekly) = weekly pay × 52</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Apply thresholds</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = annual pay</li>
                  <li>\( PT \) = primary threshold (per year)</li>
                  <li>\( UEL \) = upper earnings limit (per year)</li>
                  <li>\( r_m \) = main rate (e.g. 10%)</li>
                  <li>\( r_u \) = upper rate (e.g. 2%)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then annual employee NI is:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{NI}_{\text{employee}} = \max(0, \min(P, UEL) - PT)
                  \times r_m + \max(0, P - UEL) \times r_u \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  The calculator then divides this by 12 or 52 to give a monthly
                  or weekly figure.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Employer National Insurance</h3>
              <p>
                Employers also pay Class 1 NI on employees’ earnings above the
                <em>secondary threshold</em>. This does not reduce your
                take‑home pay but is part of your total employment cost.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( ST \) = secondary threshold (per year)</li>
                  <li>\( r_e \) = employer NI rate (e.g. 13.8%)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{NI}_{\text{employer}} = \max(0, P - ST) \times r_e \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Self‑employed National Insurance (Class 2 &amp; 4)</h3>
              <p>If you are self‑employed, you normally pay:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Class 2</strong> – a flat weekly amount if your
                  profits are above the small profits threshold.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Class 4</strong> – a percentage of your annual profits
                  between the lower and upper profits limits, plus a smaller
                  rate above the upper limit.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Class 2 (annual)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  If \( P \) (profits) ≥ small profits threshold: \[ \text{Class
                  2} = \text{weekly rate} \times 52 \] Otherwise, Class 2 = 0.
                </p>
                <p><strong>Class 4 (annual)</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( LPL \) = lower profits limit</li>
                  <li>\( UPL \) = upper profits limit</li>
                  <li>\( r_{4m} \) = main Class 4 rate</li>
                  <li>\( r_{4u} \) = upper Class 4 rate</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Class 4} = \max(0, \min(P, UPL) - LPL) \times r_{4m}
                  + \max(0, P - UPL) \times r_{4u} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Take‑home pay after NI</h3>
              <p>
                To show the impact on your pay, the calculator subtracts your NI
                from your gross pay for the chosen period:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Take‑home after NI} = \text{Gross pay} - \text{NI for
                  that period} \]
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-600">
                  Income tax, pension contributions, student loans and other
                  deductions are <strong>not</strong> included.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you are an employee earning
                <strong>£3,000 per month</strong>. Using the example thresholds
                and rates above:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Annual pay = £3,000 × 12 = £36,000.</li>
                <li>
                  Primary threshold = £12,570, upper earnings limit = £50,270.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Taxable NI band at main rate = £36,000 − £12,570 = £23,430.
                </li>
                <li>
                  All of this is below the upper earnings limit, so no
                  upper‑rate NI applies.
                </li>
                <li>Annual NI = £23,430 × 10% = £2,343.</li>
                <li>Monthly NI ≈ £2,343 ÷ 12 ≈ <strong>£195.25</strong>.</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Your estimated take‑home after NI would be £3,000 − £195.25 ≈
                <strong>£2,804.75 per month</strong>
                (before income tax and other deductions).
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is this National Insurance calculator official?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This is an independent educational tool designed to help you
                understand how NI works and to plan your finances. It is not
                affiliated with HMRC or GOV.UK and should not be relied on as a
                definitive statement of your liability.
              </p>

              <h3>Which tax year does this calculator use?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator is pre‑filled with example thresholds and rates
                for a recent UK tax year. Because NI rules can change mid‑year,
                you should always verify the latest figures on
                <a
                  href="https://www.gov.uk/national-insurance"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  target="_blank"
                  >GOV.UK</a
                >
                and update the advanced settings accordingly.
              </p>

              <h3>Does it handle irregular pay or bonuses?</h3>
              <p>
                The tool assumes a steady level of pay and annualises your
                income. If you receive large one‑off bonuses or your pay varies
                significantly, your real‑world NI in a given week or month may
                differ from the annualised estimate shown here.
              </p>

              <h3>What about National Insurance credits?</h3>
              <p>
                NI credits can help protect your entitlement to certain benefits
                when you are not paying NI (for example, if you are unemployed
                or a carer). This calculator only looks at paid contributions
                and does not model credits. For personalised advice, contact
                HMRC or a qualified adviser.
              </p>

              <h3>Where can I check my National Insurance record?</h3>
              <p>
                You can view your NI record, check for gaps and see your
                forecast State Pension on the official UK government website:
                <a
                  href="https://www.gov.uk/check-national-insurance-record"
